data.content:
## Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation Migration

### What breaks on .NET 8

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never triggered — dead code |

### Pattern classification

Your code contains three overlapping patterns:

1. **Cancellable work loop** — `while (_running)` with `Abort()` as fallback
2. **ThreadAbortException as control flow** — catch block rolls back a transaction
3. **Thread.ResetAbort** — prevents rethrow so `finally` runs cleanly
4. **Blocking call interruption** — `GetNextItem()` may block indefinitely, making `_running = false` ineffective

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back partial work (was in ThreadAbortException catch)
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly; replaces Thread.ResetAbort + continue behavior
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop — this is a design problem, not solvable with Abort().
            // Log a warning. The thread is marked IsBackground so it won't prevent exit.
            // If GetNextItem/ProcessItem truly can't cooperate, move them to a child process.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key changes explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool can't interrupt `WaitOne`, `Read`, etc. |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal — no `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard prevents swallowing unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | You control the loop — just exit it |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` then check `IsAlive` | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | `Join` blocks *until the thread exits or timeout*, which is what you actually wanted |
| No `IDisposable` | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed |

### Critical: Make `GetNextItem` cooperate

The original `Thread.Abort()` existed because `GetNextItem()` blocks. **Cancellation only works if `GetNextItem` checks the token.** Common patterns:

```csharp
// If it wraps a BlockingCollection<T>:
var item = _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel

// If it wraps a WaitHandle/ManualResetEvent:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });
if (token.IsCancellationRequested) throw new OperationCanceledException(token);

// If it wraps synchronous I/O (e.g., socket.Receive):
// Replace with async: await stream.ReadAsync(buffer, token);
// Or use a polling approach with token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(pollInterval)
```

> **If you cannot modify `GetNextItem`** (e.g., third-party code), there is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort`. Move the blocking work to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` as the last resort.

### Pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---|---|
| Forgetting to pass `token` through to `ProcessItem` and `GetNextItem` | Cancellation has no effect — the thread blocks indefinitely |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` without the `when` guard | Swallows unrelated cancellations from inner async calls |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks internal timers and registered callbacks |
| Assuming `Cancel()` stops the thread instantly | Cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint; large work items delay it |
| Removing the rollback without moving it | The `ThreadAbortException` catch had `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` — don't lose it |
